If you had a random seed, I imagine that the collision rate would be much lower.

Well now that we have a cache to save the names that we've generated, it doesn't really matter anymore. Unless I'm missing something?

Before the cache, the idea was to get the same names when you hit the command twice. It would not have worked perfectly but it would have been mostly the same.
Now that we have a cache, the name generation only matters for new entries, as existing entries just have their names taken from the local storage.
If we keep a static seed, the new entries would likely collide with entries already present, so we might as well have a random seed so as to make the collisions a lot less likely.

There shouldn't be a reimage_version API.

Why do we need that API ? This should be provided by the HostInfo.get API
Same not sure why we need that one. I do get that properties & instance are different, but both should be returned by the HostInfo.get API, based on valued updated by the background task.
It shouldn't be 'anything', but you can read the existing value and write it back to it.
It might be worth providing a better message. Also what happened if etcd can't be contacted/timeout ?

I would actually prefer that to be the other way around:

(8 comments)

It's likely missing an abstraction. I dislike the fact that 'hostname' is used an id. To me that encourages race conditions.
